                        <interp inst="t18360919-name-1155" type="given" value="JOHN BENJAMIN"></interp>JOHN BENJAMIN CLARK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a bedstead and cabinet maker, in part<lb></lb>nership with my father, John Clark, at Kennington. I employed the pri<lb></lb>soner, about a dozen times, to carry out goods—we paid him by the job—on the 24th of August, at ten o'clock in the morning, I sent him with a bedstead to Herrington, at Wandsworth, and gave him a bill and receipt—he was authorized to receive the money—I expected him back about three o'clock—he did not come—about seven o'clock I went to Mr. Herrington, who produced the receipt for the money—I apprehended the prisoner be<lb></lb>tween nine and ten o'clock that night, very much intoxicated—he said he had spent the money—he had only 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in his pocket.</p>
